content.description:
a short, steep route on the crag to the left of the "death gully" (known as Wall F). smooth rock, with the crux coming between the 2nd and 3rd bolt.

Sees partial afternoon sun, but has a large tree near it, so it can be wet.
content.location: scramble up to the base of Wall C, then continue around the arete on the trail. to the left of the death gully.

content.description: A overhanging, bolted line between the arete and Dihedral of Wall C. Solid, clean rock the whole way.
content.location:
take the fixed line up to the base of Wall C.

obvious bolted line on the left.

content.description:
This steep, crimpy slab lies directly to the right of Alan Henshaw pre-memorial.

the original line climbs straight up past the second bolt, or; climb a rock at the base, then step onto the slab, and climb rightward to a flake system for the 10a start.

first climbed in 1995 as a 10d/11a, this route originally had no name. Local legend Dallas Kloke climbed it in 1998 with a 10a variation, and officially named it.
content.protection:
5 bolts for the 11a start.

6 bolts for the 10a start.

a small piece can be placed near the top but isn't necessary.
content.location: up the fixed line for Wall C. this is the second route from the right.

content.description:
An Erie classic. A 50' tall dihedral of clean rock, with bomber pro almost the entire route.

The Crux comes in the first 10 feet, then eases off slightly the remainder of the route.

This route was discovered by Mt. Erie pioneer Alan Henshaw, then climbed and named by T. Nelson.
content.location: take the shady hollow trail up and right, then back left up a fixed line to the base of wall C. WATCH YOUR STEP!
